      "value": "Borrego Springs Unified is a rural K-12 district in the eastern desert of San Diego County. Its full reported special-education population is 667 students with an IEP, of whom 23 \u2014 about 3% \u2014 have an autism (ASD) eligibility. Roughly 91% of those autistic students spend most of the school day in a general-education classroom."
    },
    "what_this_means_for_parents": {
      "ai_disclaimer": "This summary was written by an AI model from the data points in this profile. The underlying numbers come from public California government sources, but the narrative is AI-written and may contain inaccuracies. Verify specific claims directly with the school district before making decisions.",
      "ai_generated": true,
      "ai_generated_at": "2026-05-18T03:25:32Z",
      "ai_model": "claude-opus (via Claude Code session)",
      "based_on_sources": [
        "cde_spedps",
        "ca_dashboard",
        "ocr"
      ],
      "value": "About 91% of autistic students here are in a general-education classroom for most of the day, and none are reported in a fully separate setting. Among all students with disabilities, a broader group than autism alone, 98% are in general-education classrooms most of the day. On 2024-25 state tests, students with disabilities scored about 132 points below standard in English and 182 points below in math, compared with 47 and 85 points below for students overall. Students with disabilities were chronically absent at about 25%, close to the 24% rate for all students, and were suspended at about 3%."
    }
  },
